e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are two basic ways to use artificial intelligen=
ce to predict stock prices:</p> <ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padd=
ing-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You bui=
ld a deep learning model to predict stock prices: You set up a deep neural =
net, you feed it tons of historical data about stocks, and you train it to =
figure out how that data predicts stock price returns. Then you run the mod=
el on current data, it predicts future returns, and you buy the stocks that=
 it thinks will go up.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You take some=
 deep learning model that someone else built, a large language model, one t=
hat is good at predicting=C2=A0<em>text</em>. It is trained on a huge corpu=
s of human language, and it is good at answering questions like =E2=80=9Cwr=
ite a poem about a frog in the style of W.B. Yeats.=E2=80=9D And=C2=A0<em>y=
ou=C2=A0</em>ask it questions like =E2=80=9Cwrite a report=C2=A0about wheth=
er I should buy=C2=A0Nvidia Corp. stock in the style of Warren Buffett.=E2=
=80=9D And then it trains on the writing style of Warren Buffett, which ref=
lects his thinking style, and its answer to your question =E2=80=94=C2=A0yo=
u hope =E2=80=94=C2=A0actually reflects what Buffett might say, or what he =
might say if he was a computer with a lot of time to think about the questi=
on. And because Warren Buffett is good at picking stocks, this synthetic ve=
rsion of him=C2=A0is useful to you. You read the report, and if robot Warre=
n Buffett says =E2=80=9Cbuy=E2=80=9D you buy.</li> </ol> <p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">The first approach makes obvious intuitive sense and roughly des=
cribes what various quantitative investment firms=C2=A0actually get up to: =
There might be patterns in financial data that predict future returns, and =
deep learning is a statistical technique for finding them.</p> <p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">The second approach=C2=A0seems =E2=80=A6=C2=A0sort of insa=
ne and wasteful and indirect=3F Yet also funny and charming=3F It is an app=
roach to solving the problem by first solving a much harder and more genera=
l problem: Instead of =E2=80=9Cgo through a ton of data to see what signals=
 predict whether a stock goes up,=E2=80=9D it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cconstruct =
a robot that convincingly mimics human consciousness, and then train that r=
obot to mimic the consciousness of a particular human who is good at pickin=
g stocks, and then give the robot some basic data about a stock, and then a=
sk the robot to predict whether the human would predict that the stock will=
 go up.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My impression is th=
at there are people using the first approach=C2=A0with significant success =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0this is roughly, like Renaissance Technologies =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0and the second approach is mostly me making a joke. But not=C2=A0<em>ent=
irely. </em>The second approach has some critical advantages:</p> <ol style=
=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"> <li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Somebody else =E2=80=94=C2=A0OpenAI or xAI or De=
epSeek or whoever =E2=80=94=C2=A0already built the large language model for=
 you, at great expense. If you are on the cutting edge of machine learning =
and can afford to pay for huge quantities of data and=C2=A0researchers and=
=C2=A0computing capacity, go ahead and build a stock-predicting model, but =
if you are just, say, <em>an academic</em>, using someone else=E2=80=99s mo=
del is probably easier. The large language model companies release their mo=
dels pretty widely. The stock model companies do not. You can=E2=80=99t, li=
ke, pay $20 a month for Rennaissance=E2=80=99s stock price model.</li> <li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Because the large language model=E2=80=99s ou=
tput is=C2=A0<em>prose</em>, its reasoning=C2=A0is=C2=A0<em>explainable=C2=
=A0</em>in a way that the stock model is not. The stock model is like =E2=
=80=9CI have looked at every possible combination of 100,000 data time seri=
es=C2=A0and constructed a signal that is a nonlinear combination of 37,314 =
of them, and the signal says Nvidia will go up,=E2=80=9D and if you ask why=
,=C2=A0the model will say =E2=80=9Cwell, the 37,314 data sets.=E2=80=9D You=
 just have to trust it. Whereas robot Warren Buffett will write you a nice =
little report, with <em>reasons=C2=A0</em>you should buy Nvidia. The reason=
s might be entirely hallucinated, but you can go check. I <a href=3D"https:=
